The phrase ‘to become who or what one is’ is an adaptation of a line from Pindar’s Second Pythian Ode. The individual is a ‘piece of fate’ meaning it cannot be fundamentally recast in the image of some external (i.e. moral) value. To do so would be a double betrayal of oneself, a deviation or distortion of the life one is, resulting in all kinds of physical or spiritual degeneration. Nor is it a question of choosing to shape oneself in any way – for the individual will never be fundamentally reconfigured as who she is – but rather the shape of her actions is changed by the inner drive. Thus, in both cases the latter is the one who created the figure of character in the first place.

The second aspect of creation is that the first act of creation is in the domain of values. Waking life is ‘formless’ consciousness, the object of our enquiry into being consciousness. Waking life is first, the self- image of God and the self- image of gods; second, the real-world, such as the real estate or construction materialistic world. Third, and most importantly, waking life is the realisation of the mythic innocence of antiquity. Its beauty and its peace of the world is its ‘future’.

